## 5.2 Pharmacokinetic properties

Absorption

Absorption of {{ drug.name }} is rapid although the amount absorbed varies. The mean absolute bioavailability for {{ drug.name }} is about 50%.

When {{ drug.name }} is taken with food, the reduction in the area under the plasma concentration-time curve ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}-∞) of {{ drug.name }} varies from approximately 6% ({{ drug.strength }} dose) to approximately 19% ({{ drug.strength }} dose). By 3 hours after administration plasma concentrations are similar whether {{ drug.name }} is taken fasting or with food.

Linearity/non-linearity

The small reduction in {{ drug.molecular_formula }} is not expected to cause a reduction in the therapeutic efficacy.

There is no linear relationship between doses and plasma levels. Cmax and to a lesser extent {{ drug.molecular_formula }} increase disproportionately at doses above {{ drug.strength }}.

Distribution

{{ drug.name }} is largely bound to plasma protein (> 99.5%), mainly albumin and alpha-1 acid glycoprotein. The mean steady state apparent volume of distribution (Vdss) is approximately 500 l.

Biotransformation

{{ drug.name }} is metabolised by conjugation to the glucuronide of the parent compound. No pharmacological activity has been shown for the conjugate.

Elimination

{{ drug.name }} is characterised by biexponential decay pharmacokinetics with a terminal elimination half-life of > 20 hours. The maximum plasma concentration (Cmax) and, to a smaller extent, the area under the plasma concentration-time curve ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) increase disproportionately with dose. There is no evidence of clinically relevant accumulation of {{ drug.name }} taken at the recommended dose. Plasma concentrations were higher in females than in males, without relevant influence on efficacy.

After {{ drug.route_of_administration }} (and {{ drug.route_of_administration }}) administration {{ drug.name }} is nearly exclusively excreted with the faeces, mainly as unchanged compound. Cumulative urinary excretion is < 1% of dose. Total plasma clearance (Cltot) is high (approximately 1,{{ drug.strength }}/min) compared with hepatic blood flow (about 1,{{ drug.strength }}/min).

Special Populations

Paediatric population

The pharmacokinetics of two doses of {{ drug.name }} were assessed as a secondary objective in hypertensive patients (n = 57) aged 6 to < 18 years after taking {{ drug.name }} {{ drug.strength }}/kg or {{ drug.strength }}/kg over a four-week treatment period. Pharmacokinetic objectives included the determination of the steady-state of {{ drug.name }} in children and adolescents, and investigation of age-related differences. Although the study was too small for a meaningful assessment of the pharmacokinetics of children under 12 years of age, the results are generally consistent with the findings in adults and confirm the non-linearity of {{ drug.name }}, particularly for Cmax.

Gender

Gender differences in plasma concentrations were observed, Cmax and {{ drug.molecular_formula }} being approximately 3-and 2-fold higher, respectively, in females compared to males.

Elderly

The pharmacokinetics of {{ drug.name }} do not differ between the elderly and those younger than 65 years.

Renal impairment

In patients with mild to moderate and severe renal impairment, doubling of plasma concentrations was observed. However, lower plasma concentrations were observed in patients with renal insufficiency undergoing dialysis. {{ drug.name }} is highly bound to plasma protein in renal-insufficient patients and cannot be removed by dialysis. The elimination half-life is not changed in patients with renal impairment.

Hepatic impairment

Pharmacokinetic studies in patients with hepatic impairment showed an increase in absolute bioavailability up to nearly 100 %. The elimination half-life is not changed in patients with hepatic impairment.
